Note:
Runa Mathematical Symbol Function Definitions

Implements the actual computational functions that correspond to mathematical Unicode symbols.
This module connects the lexical mathematical symbols to their functional implementations,
enabling seamless mathematical computation using standard mathematical notation.

Features:
- Summation operator (∑) with range support
- Product operator (∏) with range support  
- Integration functions (∫) with numerical methods
- Greek letter constants (π, e) with high precision
- Set theory operations (∈, ∪, ∩, ⊂)
- Logic operations (∀, ∃, ¬, ∧, ∨)
- Comparison functions (≤, ≥, ≠, ≈)
- Special functions (√, ∛, ⌊, ⌈)
:End Note

Import "collections" as Collections
Import "builtins" as Builtins

Note: Core mathematical constants using Unicode symbols
Let π be 3.14159265358979323846264338327950288
Let e be 2.71828182845904523536028747135266249
Let φ be 1.61803398874989484820458683436563811  Note: Golden ratio
Let ∞ be Infinity

Note: Summation operator implementation
Process called "∑" that takes sequence as List[Number] returns Number:
    Note: Sum all elements in a sequence
    Let total be 0
    For each element in sequence:
        Set total to total plus element
    Return total

Process called "∑" that takes start as Integer and end as Integer and func as Function[Integer, Number] returns Number:
    Note: Sum function over range [start, end]
    Let total be 0
    For i from start to end:
        Set total to total plus func(i)
    Return total

Note: Product operator implementation  
Process called "∏" that takes sequence as List[Number] returns Number:
    Note: Multiply all elements in a sequence
    Let product be 1
    For each element in sequence:
        Set product to product multiplied by element
    Return product

Process called "∏" that takes start as Integer and end as Integer and func as Function[Integer, Number] returns Number:
    Note: Product of function over range [start, end]
    Let product be 1
    For i from start to end:
        Set product to product multiplied by func(i)
    Return product

Note: Integration functions (numerical)
Process called "∫" that takes func as Function[Number, Number] and a as Number and b as Number returns Number:
    Note: Numerical integration using trapezoidal rule
    Let n be 1000  Note: Number of subdivisions
    Let h be (b minus a) divided by n
    Let sum be (func(a) plus func(b)) divided by 2
    
    For i from 1 to n minus 1:
        Let x be a plus (i multiplied by h)
        Set sum to sum plus func(x)
    
    Return sum multiplied by h

Process called "∫" that takes func as Function[Number, Number] and a as Number and b as Number and method as String returns Number:
    Note: Integration with specified numerical method
    Match method:
        When "trapezoidal":
            Return ∫(func, a, b)
        When "simpson":
            Return simpson_integration with func as func and a as a and b as b
        When "gaussian":
            Return gaussian_quadrature with func as func and a as a and b as b
        Otherwise:
            Return ∫(func, a, b)

Process called "simpson_integration" that takes func as Function[Number, Number] and a as Number and b as Number returns Number:
    Note: Simpson's rule for numerical integration
    Let n be 1000  Note: Must be even
    Let h be (b minus a) divided by n
    Let sum be func(a) plus func(b)
    
    For i from 1 to n minus 1:
        Let x be a plus (i multiplied by h)
        If i modulo 2 is equal to 0:
            Set sum to sum plus (2 multiplied by func(x))
        Otherwise:
            Set sum to sum plus (4 multiplied by func(x))
    
    Return (h divided by 3) multiplied by sum

Note: Square root and nth root functions
Process called "√" that takes x as Number returns Number:
    Note: Square root function
    If x is less than 0:
        Throw MathError with message as "Square root of negative number"
    Return power with base as x and exponent as 0.5

Process called "∛" that takes x as Number returns Number:
    Note: Cube root function  
    If x is less than 0:
        Return 0 minus power with base as (0 minus x) and exponent as (1 divided by 3)
    Return power with base as x and exponent as (1 divided by 3)

Process called "nth_root" that takes x as Number and n as Integer returns Number:
    Note: nth root function
    If n is equal to 0:
        Throw MathError with message as "Cannot take 0th root"
    If x is less than 0 and n modulo 2 is equal to 0:
        Throw MathError with message as "Even root of negative number"
    
    Let exponent be 1 divided by n
    If x is less than 0:
        Return 0 minus power with base as (0 minus x) and exponent as exponent
    Return power with base as x and exponent as exponent

Note: Floor and ceiling functions
Process called "⌊" that takes x as Number returns Integer:
    Note: Floor function - largest integer ≤ x
    Return floor with value as x

Process called "⌈" that takes x as Number returns Integer:
    Note: Ceiling function - smallest integer ≥ x
    Return ceiling with value as x

Note: Set membership and operations
Process called "∈" that takes element as Any and set as Set[Any] returns Boolean:
    Note: Set membership test
    Return set.contains(element)

Process called "∉" that takes element as Any and set as Set[Any] returns Boolean:
    Note: Not in set test
    Return not set.contains(element)

Process called "⊂" that takes subset as Set[Any] and superset as Set[Any] returns Boolean:
    Note: Proper subset test
    If subset.size() is greater than or equal to superset.size():
        Return false
    Return subset.is_subset_of(superset)

Process called "⊆" that takes subset as Set[Any] and superset as Set[Any] returns Boolean:
    Note: Subset or equal test
    Return subset.is_subset_of(superset)

Process called "⊃" that takes superset as Set[Any] and subset as Set[Any] returns Boolean:
    Note: Proper superset test
    Return ⊂(subset, superset)

Process called "⊇" that takes superset as Set[Any] and subset as Set[Any] returns Boolean:
    Note: Superset or equal test
    Return ⊆(subset, superset)

Process called "∪" that takes set1 as Set[Any] and set2 as Set[Any] returns Set[Any]:
    Note: Set union operation
    Return set1.union(set2)

Process called "∩" that takes set1 as Set[Any] and set2 as Set[Any] returns Set[Any]:
    Note: Set intersection operation
    Return set1.intersection(set2)

Process called "∖" that takes set1 as Set[Any] and set2 as Set[Any] returns Set[Any]:
    Note: Set difference operation
    Return set1.difference(set2)

Note: Logic operations
Process called "∀" that takes predicate as Function[Any, Boolean] and collection as List[Any] returns Boolean:
    Note: Universal quantifier - true if predicate holds for all elements
    For each element in collection:
        If not predicate(element):
            Return false
    Return true

Process called "∃" that takes predicate as Function[Any, Boolean] and collection as List[Any] returns Boolean:
    Note: Existential quantifier - true if predicate holds for at least one element
    For each element in collection:
        If predicate(element):
            Return true
    Return false

Process called "∄" that takes predicate as Function[Any, Boolean] and collection as List[Any] returns Boolean:
    Note: Non-existence quantifier - true if predicate holds for no elements
    Return not ∃(predicate, collection)

Process called "¬" that takes value as Boolean returns Boolean:
    Note: Logical negation
    Return not value

Process called "∧" that takes a as Boolean and b as Boolean returns Boolean:
    Note: Logical AND
    Return a and b

Process called "∨" that takes a as Boolean and b as Boolean returns Boolean:
    Note: Logical OR
    Return a or b

Process called "⊕" that takes a as Boolean and b as Boolean returns Boolean:
    Note: Logical XOR (exclusive or)
    Return (a and not b) or (not a and b)

Process called "⇒" that takes a as Boolean and b as Boolean returns Boolean:
    Note: Logical implication (if a then b)
    Return not a or b

Process called "⇔" that takes a as Boolean and b as Boolean returns Boolean:
    Note: Logical equivalence (if and only if)
    Return (a and b) or (not a and not b)

Note: Comparison operations  
Process called "≤" that takes a as Number and b as Number returns Boolean:
    Note: Less than or equal to
    Return a is less than or equal to b

Process called "≥" that takes a as Number and b as Number returns Boolean:
    Note: Greater than or equal to
    Return a is greater than or equal to b

Process called "≠" that takes a as Any and b as Any returns Boolean:
    Note: Not equal to
    Return not (a is equal to b)

Process called "≈" that takes a as Number and b as Number returns Boolean:
    Note: Approximately equal (default tolerance)
    Let tolerance be 1e-10
    Return abs(a minus b) is less than tolerance

Process called "≈" that takes a as Number and b as Number and tolerance as Number returns Boolean:
    Note: Approximately equal with specified tolerance
    Return abs(a minus b) is less than tolerance

Process called "≡" that takes a as Any and b as Any returns Boolean:
    Note: Identical to (strict equality)
    Return a is identical to b

Note: Differential operators
Process called "∂" that takes func as Function[Number, Number] and x as Number returns Number:
    Note: Partial derivative using finite differences
    Let h be 1e-8
    Return (func(x plus h) minus func(x minus h)) divided by (2 multiplied by h)

Process called "∇" that takes func as Function[List[Number], Number] and point as List[Number] returns List[Number]:
    Note: Gradient vector using finite differences
    Let gradient be list containing
    Let h be 1e-8
    
    For i from 0 to length of point minus 1:
        Let point_plus be copy_list with list as point
        Let point_minus be copy_list with list as point
        Set point_plus[i] to point_plus[i] plus h
        Set point_minus[i] to point_minus[i] minus h
        
        Let partial_derivative be (func(point_plus) minus func(point_minus)) divided by (2 multiplied by h)
        Add partial_derivative to gradient
    
    Return gradient

Note: Special mathematical functions
Process called "factorial" that takes n as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Factorial function (could be used with ∏)
    If n is less than 0:
        Throw MathError with message as "Factorial of negative number"
    If n is equal to 0 or n is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    Return ∏(1, n, lambda i: i)

Process called "combination" that takes n as Integer and k as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Binomial coefficient C(n,k)
    If k is greater than n or k is less than 0:
        Return 0
    If k is equal to 0 or k is equal to n:
        Return 1
    
    Return factorial(n) divided by (factorial(k) multiplied by factorial(n minus k))

Process called "permutation" that takes n as Integer and k as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Permutation P(n,k)
    If k is greater than n or k is less than 0:
        Return 0
    Return factorial(n) divided by factorial(n minus k)

Note: Trigonometric functions with symbolic support
Process called "sin_π" that takes x as Number returns Number:
    Note: sin(x * π) - more accurate for multiples of π
    Return sin(x multiplied by π)

Process called "cos_π" that takes x as Number returns Number:
    Note: cos(x * π) - more accurate for multiples of π
    Return cos(x multiplied by π)

Process called "tan_π" that takes x as Number returns Number:
    Note: tan(x * π) - more accurate for multiples of π
    Return tan(x multiplied by π)

Note: Complex number support for mathematical symbols
Type called "ComplexNumber":
    real as Number
    imaginary as Number

Process called "complex_add" that takes a as ComplexNumber and b as ComplexNumber returns ComplexNumber:
    Return ComplexNumber with:
        real as a.real plus b.real
        imaginary as a.imaginary plus b.imaginary

Process called "complex_multiply" that takes a as ComplexNumber and b as ComplexNumber returns ComplexNumber:
    Let real_part be (a.real multiplied by b.real) minus (a.imaginary multiplied by b.imaginary)
    Let imag_part be (a.real multiplied by b.imaginary) plus (a.imaginary multiplied by b.real)
    Return ComplexNumber with:
        real as real_part
        imaginary as imag_part

Note: Mathematical sequence and series functions
Process called "fibonacci" that takes n as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Fibonacci sequence using golden ratio formula
    If n is less than 0:
        Throw MathError with message as "Fibonacci index must be non-negative"
    
    Let sqrt5 be √(5)
    Let phi_n be power with base as φ and exponent as n
    Let psi_n be power with base as (1 minus φ) and exponent as n
    
    Return round((phi_n minus psi_n) divided by sqrt5)

Process called "geometric_series" that takes a as Number and r as Number and n as Integer returns Number:
    Note: Sum of geometric series: a + ar + ar² + ... + ar^(n-1)
    If abs(r minus 1) is less than 1e-10:
        Return a multiplied by n
    Return a multiplied by (1 minus power(r, n)) divided by (1 minus r)

Process called "arithmetic_series" that takes a as Number and d as Number and n as Integer returns Number:
    Note: Sum of arithmetic series: na + n(n-1)d/2
    Return (n multiplied by a) plus ((n multiplied by (n minus 1) multiplied by d) divided by 2)

Note: Statistical functions using mathematical symbols
Process called "mean" that takes data as List[Number] returns Number:
    Note: Arithmetic mean using summation
    Return ∑(data) divided by length of data

Process called "variance" that takes data as List[Number] returns Number:
    Note: Population variance using summation
    Let μ be mean(data)
    Let squared_diffs be list containing
    For each x in data:
        Add power(x minus μ, 2) to squared_diffs
    Return ∑(squared_diffs) divided by length of data

Process called "standard_deviation" that takes data as List[Number] returns Number:
    Note: Standard deviation (σ)
    Return √(variance(data))

Note: Integration bounds and limits
Process called "definite_integral" that takes expr as String and variable as String and lower as Number and upper as Number returns Number:
    Note: Symbolic integration interface (would need symbolic math engine)
    Note: For now, this is a placeholder for future symbolic integration
    Throw NotImplementedError with message as "Symbolic integration not yet implemented"

Process called "limit" that takes func as Function[Number, Number] and approach as Number returns Number:
    Note: Numerical limit calculation
    Let h be 1e-10
    Let left_limit be func(approach minus h)
    Let right_limit be func(approach plus h)
    
    If abs(left_limit minus right_limit) is less than 1e-8:
        Return (left_limit plus right_limit) divided by 2
    Otherwise:
        Throw MathError with message as "Limit does not exist"

Note: Utility functions for mathematical operations
Process called "copy_list" that takes list as List[Any] returns List[Any]:
    Let copied be list containing
    For each item in list:
        Add item to copied
    Return copied

Process called "power" that takes base as Number and exponent as Number returns Number:
    Note: Power function implementation
    If base is equal to 0 and exponent is less than or equal to 0:
        Throw MathError with message as "Invalid power operation"
    Return base raised to exponent

Process called "abs" that takes x as Number returns Number:
    Note: Absolute value function
    If x is less than 0:
        Return 0 minus x
    Return x

Process called "round" that takes x as Number returns Integer:
    Note: Round to nearest integer
    Return floor(x plus 0.5)

Process called "floor" that takes x as Number returns Integer:
    Note: Floor function - largest integer ≤ x
    Let integer_part be x as Integer
    If x is greater than or equal to 0 or x is equal to integer_part as Number:
        Return integer_part
    Otherwise:
        Return integer_part minus 1

Process called "ceiling" that takes x as Number returns Integer:
    Note: Ceiling function - smallest integer ≥ x
    Let integer_part be x as Integer
    If x is less than or equal to 0 or x is equal to integer_part as Number:
        Return integer_part
    Otherwise:
        Return integer_part plus 1

Process called "sin" that takes x as Number returns Number:
    Note: Sine function (would use built-in math library)
    Return builtin_sin(x)

Process called "cos" that takes x as Number returns Number:
    Note: Cosine function (would use built-in math library)
    Return builtin_cos(x)

Process called "tan" that takes x as Number returns Number:
    Note: Tangent function (would use built-in math library)
    Return builtin_tan(x)

Note: Error types for mathematical operations
Type called "MathError":
    message as String

Type called "NotImplementedError":
    message as String

Note: Export all mathematical symbol functions
Process called "get_symbol_function" that takes symbol as String returns Optional[Function]:
    Note: Get function implementation for a mathematical symbol
    Match symbol:
        When "∑":
            Return Some(∑)
        When "∏":
            Return Some(∏)
        When "∫":
            Return Some(∫)
        When "√":
            Return Some(√)
        When "∛":
            Return Some(∛)
        When "⌊":
            Return Some(⌊)
        When "⌈":
            Return Some(⌈)
        When "∈":
            Return Some(∈)
        When "∉":
            Return Some(∉)
        When "⊂":
            Return Some(⊂)
        When "⊆":
            Return Some(⊆)
        When "⊃":
            Return Some(⊃)
        When "⊇":
            Return Some(⊇)
        When "∪":
            Return Some(∪)
        When "∩":
            Return Some(∩)
        When "∖":
            Return Some(∖)
        When "∀":
            Return Some(∀)
        When "∃":
            Return Some(∃)
        When "∄":
            Return Some(∄)
        When "¬":
            Return Some(¬)
        When "∧":
            Return Some(∧)
        When "∨":
            Return Some(∨)
        When "⊕":
            Return Some(⊕)
        When "⇒":
            Return Some(⇒)
        When "⇔":
            Return Some(⇔)
        When "≤":
            Return Some(≤)
        When "≥":
            Return Some(≥)
        When "≠":
            Return Some(≠)
        When "≈":
            Return Some(≈)
        When "≡":
            Return Some(≡)
        When "∂":
            Return Some(∂)
        When "∇":
            Return Some(∇)
        Otherwise:
            Return None

Note: Integration with compiler for symbol resolution
Process called "resolve_mathematical_symbol" that takes symbol as String and context as CompilerContext returns Optional[FunctionBinding]:
    Note: Resolve mathematical symbol to function binding for compiler
    Let symbol_func be get_symbol_function with symbol as symbol
    If symbol_func is not None:
        Return Some(FunctionBinding with:
            symbol as symbol
            function as symbol_func
            module as "math.symbolic_functions"
            signature as infer_function_signature with func as symbol_func)
    Return None

Type called "FunctionBinding":
    symbol as String
    function as Function
    module as String
    signature as FunctionSignature

Type called "FunctionSignature":
    parameters as List[Parameter]
    return_type as String
    overloads as List[FunctionSignature]

Type called "Parameter":
    name as String
    type as String
    optional as Boolean